3,684 Likes
Luma AI just dropped
Ray3.2
, and the pitch is simple: you direct, the AI shoots. You're no longer just=
 typing prompts and hoping for the best. You're actually controlling the sc=
ene.
The big question: what changed? A lot. Here's what you can now do:
Up to 16 keyframes
per clip, so you control exactly how motion and pacing unfold, frame by fra=
me
Track up to 8 faces at once, preserving expressions, posture, and gestures =
across the whole shot
Export native
16-bit HDR in EXR format
, which drops straight into color grading and VFX pipelines
Reframe shots after the fact, swap backgrounds, change aspect ratios, witho=
ut reshooting anything
Generate clips
up to 20 seconds at 1080p
, long enough to build real scenes
The other big thing: Ray3.2 now has an
API
. For the first time, you can plug Luma's video generation directly into yo=
ur own tools, render farms, or custom pipelines. No middleware needed.
